<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-822-435  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 822 435.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Dec 20 1990 v16 n26 p44(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PC Light runs multi-user software. (Softworks Development Corp.'sworkstation) (New Products) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Softworks Development Corp. (Product introduction)Intelligent Graphics Corp. (Products).andO;Product:   Softworks Development PC Light (Workstation) (Productintroduction)VM-386 MultiUser (Computer program) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionWorkstationsDisplay Capacity.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>PC Light runs multi-user softwareandM;MENOMONEE FALLS, Wis.andP;  -- Softworks Development Corp. has introduced PCLight, a high-performance multi-user display system that allows users to runmultiple DOS applications concurrently because of an exclusive softwarepackage from Intelligent Graphics Corp. (IGC) of San Jose, Calif.andM;The PC Light multi-user display system empowers a single 386 or 486, ISA-orEISA-based computer to support one to eight low-cost graphics workstations,which connect to the host via a high-speed fibre optic communication ring.andP;  Acomplete PC Light workstation retails for under $1,500 (U.S.) per station.andM;Softwork's multi-user display system includes PC Light VM/386 software, basedon IGC's VM/386 multi-user software.andM;The PC Light VM/386 software features a virtual machine architecture whichallows each PC Light workstation to act like a separate PC running DOS.andM;The PC Light runs &quot;real&quot; mode 386 software and supports shrinkwrapped DOSapplications including Microsoft Windows 3.0.andM;According to the company, because the PC Light VM/386 software supports DOS3.1 file and record locking, network versions of database applications suchas dBase, Foxbase and Paradox are compatible with the PC Light system.andO;</TEXT></DOC>